segments.text: when they first had their P.E.
program the instructor came in and told them there's no ladies rooms here we're going to have to go meet in the library so that was their start of P.E.
but tales of being harassed going to school that they had
have their heels kicked and their toes stepped on by fellas in the corps saying, why don't you go to TWU?
You don't belong here with us.
So they had to put up with a lot of that initially.
But after those, what I think, relatively few instances, it was all for the best and accepted.
What about the reception of that first female faculty member?
How was she received in the department and in the college, as you recall?
In the college pretty well, and I think in the college pretty well as far as committee assignments and things go.
But that was a relative rarity, too.
As you look back on it, did you all hire her in an affirmative action posture because she was female, or did you hire her because she was the best person?
No, I wanted her to cover the community recreation aspects that we wanted to do.
I don't remember honestly if that was a rear guard action against health and physical education or something we wanted to do anyway.
In those early years, did you run up into any brick walls, any obstacles that were difficult to get around in the department's growth and progress?
No.
In fact, I think among some of the people, I was a constant irritant.
We were growing fast.
Rutter supported us every time.
I don't know if he told... You know, you have to remember, over in the Koch building, when I came here, the whole administrative structure of the university could sit in one room.
I think they had like 46 chairs in there.
President Rutter had three assistants.
The academic council would be all the deans, all the department heads.

and Andy Suttle as research I think and some Graf or Goff or something Bill Graf as academics undergraduate academics that was all there was and so we were a pretty tight group little bunch and I remember President Rutter who was a very stout man getting up one day and saying I'm just your old
pot-bellied president.
He said, you fellas make the decisions about what to teach.
I'll just go get you the money.
Kind of an earthy, down to earth kind of a guy with no pretensions about academic stuff.
And it operated pretty well like that in terms of getting approval.
So I was able to get the courses
We were always building a curriculum, and most of the early courses I taught myself the first time, breaking them in.
It seems wonderful to have that much time available at that time.
And another thing, Haskell, this is out of context, but I'm proud of several things.
We had one of the first girls as an undergraduate.
We had the first girl graduate in the Corps.
And I had the first black
varsity member of the football team.
Who was it?
J.T.
Thomas.
Oh yes.

He went into the National Park Service along with Dabney, and he also had some of these experiences you know of the football players rubbing his hair for good luck before a game, but he stuck it out and earned his
letter with the football team.
So those were pretty significant changes along the way, too.
Now, with the support you enjoyed from President Rutter and so forth, did any of your colleagues ever accuse you and the department of being his pets?
Yes.
How was that made known?
How was that expressed?
Oh, I don't know.
Just bantering, I guess.
I don't think we were ever given anything that we didn't work for.
And in recognition of what we did, somebody always made it possible to move to another place.
Went from the plant science building to the heap building.
From the heap building, as I grew, we couldn't get any other place together and started fragmenting.
And finally, I had people in the old bioscience building.
You remember where that was?
before the new one was built, had four or five offices there.
I think we were in five different buildings during that time.
And it finally got to me because we had a secretary that took mail around to all these different places.
And one day I looked for this particular secretary and she didn't come back until almost noon.
kind of reamed her out because I thought that she'd been just off having lunch or something somewhere.
And she said, no, Dr. So-and-so sent me to get his laundry, his cleaning over at the laundry.
Well, that did it.
And I said, we got to get back into a single place.
And fortunately, and I know this was in 70, was able to bargain our way into the horse barn.
The horse barn at that time was up for demolition, Garrigan's barn.
It had been used for an extension warehouse for undistributed publications.
And then there was a proposal to make it the golf headquarters.
Who had built the golf course in 51?
You were here.
No, no, not in 51, 59 for me.
Oh, well, 51 I think the golf course was first built.

and they wanted to have the horse barn be the golf clubhouse and sales office and everything and president rudder asked me and i argued against it i said it's it's a good building to make a good academic building i'd like to be in there
The other side of the coin is I think it's dangerous to have people with golf carts and walking back and forth from this side of the road to get to the golf course.
Well, they eventually approved me moving into there and gave us a massive amount of money, I think $130,000 to renovate it for offices and classrooms and laboratories.
And every student, to my knowledge, that was
in that building, in the old horse barn during the two years we were there, considers that the salad days of the department.
The upstairs was,

unlivable but the wives came in with bandanas around their head and they scrubbed and cleaned I rassled up enough surplus furniture to put offices office furniture and desks up there for them we finally made a faculty conference area up there and that was one happy family that department at that time in fact curious thing people will organize no matter what

you do they like structure and I realized after we were in there about in the first year six months nine months that there was a structure going as new students came in they had to have a desk on this side of the upstairs loft each semester as somebody graduated they were allowed to move up one desk toward the other end as far as I could tell there was no difference in the air conditioning or the view or the lights or anything else but
You could move up until finally you were the senior grad students on the other end of that room.
But that was a good place except we outgrew it so rapidly.
Now, during those years, did you or anyone else attempt any kind of social events to pull the department's parts together?
We did a lot of that.
Describe those, please.

Well, we had receptions every semester for the graduating students, and Dorothy and I, bless her heart, we did those initially at our house, borrowed card tables from all around the neighborhood, and invited both the graduating students plus their spouse or girlfriend and parents, if they were in town,
to come to that.
We had them in every room of the house, cooked for them.

In the very first year or so, I bought a lot out at Carter Lake, intending, that's only three or four miles out of town to the south here, intending to build a summer place for us that's on a hill where you could look and see the campus from the top of that hill.
And monthly,
I took all the students in the department out there for a wiener roast on the bank of that little 50-acre lake.
A couple of the Dabney brothers, for example, played 12-string guitars.
We'd just sing cowboy songs and have a good old time.
We organized a recreation and park student club right away.
And another thing I tried to do that was very successful, when I got here, A&M was organized, and you've been here so you know this, on the basis of class ring year.
Like President Rutter was 32, class of 32, and somebody else 37 or 43 or whatever.
And I saw that as a layer cake.
And I said, you know, in our department,
The faculty bought into this.
We want to have a layer cake, but a slice of cake.
It doesn't matter what year they are, freshman to senior or graduate, they're all part of the department.
And so I tried not to do away with the class ring year, but to emphasize the departmental affiliation.
And I'll tell you what that did, Haskell.
It developed into a national network where our students
when they graduated, would recommend other students to come here or would hire our graduates.
And that's still going on.
So that's a little sidelined.
What kind of get-togethers did you have for the faculty and staff?
We had Christmas parties.
Probably too many parties of different stuff.
We had noontime domino tournaments.
You know, for those that didn't want to go out to eat, just sat around and would kibitz or play dominoes.
We invited the secretarial staff to these kind of things, and I think that made them feel more a part of the thing as well.
As things were developing, when did you begin to feel that you were making national impact?
people were beginning to recognize what was happening here.
Five years?
Four years?
Well, I was elected president of our national association, the Society of Park and Recreation Educators, which was about 600 members.
Because, you know, we didn't have a product to sell.
We didn't
Let me go back a little ways.
You mentioned Texas Tech.
Texas Tech owned the Parks and Wildlife Department.
They had been feeding, they started in 52.
So they had a 15 year head start on us.
And they had consequently mid-career graduates in there and they wouldn't hire any Aggies.
They wanted
They'd go to extremes to get graduates at Texas Tech into the Parks and Wildlife.
We had a very hard time busting into that, and we eventually did.
Why did I say that?
Why is that relevant?

about making the mark and being recognized i saw because we didn't have students out in these agencies i saw my role largely nationally as a tub thumper and so i went to all these meetings and probably made a nuisance of myself talking about all the good things that were happening at a m they couldn't discount us because we had the full professors who had good reputations in their own fields and they were on the programs and

all of that kind of stuff if we'd had to start with assistant profs and instructors we couldn't have done that so we were I think pretty successful in getting people out and known and visible around the country and that fed us if you look at our early enrollments most of our undergraduates were Texas kids
Most of our graduate students were out of state.
They were here, usually hated it, didn't like the weather or anything, and then they left as soon as they got the degree.
But they wanted the degree from A&M.
And so that helped as far as this national reputation.
So that by 10 years, we were recognized internationally as well as nationally.
But you see, when did President Rutter die?
70, wasn't it?
That was critical, those first five formative years.
I did try to deliver what he'd ask of us, and I think we got there, but I so often wish that he'd remained another five years or so.
Do you recall any time whenever he said to you in any fashion, made some comment that you were producing what he hoped you would?
Yeah, yeah.
Do you remember?
No, there was just always that feeling of support and a pat on the back with him.
And you know, perhaps he did the same with everybody.
I don't know.
But I always felt that, just confident of his support.
Now, did he ever kind of accost you about anything?
You didn't do this or didn't do that.

No, he laughed at me one time because, again, in trying to get more visibility on the campus, we had what was like, at Michigan State had been called Farmer's Week with a lot of displays and equipment companies and seed companies and all of that.
And we had something similar.
here every spring where all the departments put up a display and staffed it with students over in DeWare Field House.
One year I remember I, this is largely for high school kids coming to persuade them to come to A&M after they graduated.
One year I got the faculty with me and we went over with several camp stoves, kerosene camp stoves,
And we cooked pancakes for all comers.
Well, nobody had ever done anything like this.
I mean, you know, these were scholarly.
And I caught help from my department head friends in agriculture for turning this into a circus.
That was one year.
This was three years in a row.
They didn't like the pancakes and the tents and stuff.
We were doing a display on outdoor camping.
Well, what's more sensible than cooking?
But instead of just pretending to cook pancakes, we actually cooked them, put syrup on them, and gave them to all the kids and all the people and the mothers coming by.
Second year, I got a all-terrain vehicle, one of these little four-wheel kind of things from downtown at the equipment company, and came out, and we gave rides to the kids and to their parents.

And I remember one Texas mommy with her big hairdo, and she wanted to ride in that thing, and she had a tight hobble skirt on, and trying to get up over and into that was a comedy, but she wanted to ride in that thing.
That didn't go over very good, riding kids around out of doors.
The third year, I made 3,000 of these for just a few dollars.
And it said TMU, Click with Recreation and Parks.
And I gave one of these to,
every kid had a basket that came to our little display and the kids would come, where's the clickers, where's the clickers?
And I don't know if it'll even click anymore.
Well, I heard about that from the bus drivers.
They said, whoever gave these damn things to these kids, they drove me nuts all the way home in the bus.
Don't let them do that anymore.
So that's what President Rutter laughed at me about.
He said, you know, you've done some highly unorthodox thing, and I've heard from some of your colleagues over there in agriculture that you're turning it into a circus.
And I said, yeah, but we're getting students from high school.
Now, he died somewhat close to 30 years ago right now.
Do you recall any of your last conversation or anything with him?
No.
Actually, I was at a conference at Galveston when we got news that he had died suddenly of a stroke.
One month before his 60th birthday.
Good grief.
So he did not qualify for his veteran's benefits.
Is that right?
And Congressman Olin Teague, his classmate, chairman of the Veterans Affairs Committee at that time, could not get an exception made.
How tragic.
Well, I remember being absolutely stunned, and I think his name was,
Butcher, Vice President of University of Texas, had a plane there and agreed to have me come with him back to A&M.
So we flew back the same afternoon that we got the news.
He had a push-pull plane, one with a propeller on each end.
And we flew back together talking about that and the implications that this meant for the school and for the state.
And can I say something that I hope you'll delete from this?
We were talking about Mr. Rutter's death.
He is succeeded that fall by Jack Williams.
And in a year or so, Vice President for Academic Affairs, as we then called it, Horace Byers, is succeeded by John Calhoun.
When those two men came into the administration, did that change in any way the momentum that you all had underway in Recreation and Parks?
Were they supportive of the efforts y'all?
I think we were established well enough that it didn't make a whole lot of difference.
We weren't, you know, personally under the wing of President Rutter anymore.
But you're implying that you didn't need to be.
We didn't need to be because we matured enough, I guess, to have people on

the graduate faculty advisory committee and this and that kind of committee and so on and we had moved out of the horse barn to goodwin hall which was i think a major advantage and we were there quite a long time right next to the administration building
I forget how many years, quite a long time Haskell, because that was supposed to be torn down, but we could talk all afternoon about the stories of life in that place.
Share a few of them.
Well, the building was old and supposed to be knocked down and it housed the four departments of business.
whatever they were, and I was able to get on the, you know you had to plan about three years in advance to get a move to another building.
And at one point I was, you know you talk about my relations on the campus, when we get in these department head meetings some of the guys would say,

know somebody's got to put a noose about this reed he's going to surround the damn campus and he'll own all of it because i was here and there and peace pieces of department in a lot of different places but but goodwin hall put us back together in a good central location i liked it right there on the drill field and uh the way the building

was constructed, apparently it was built in two sections with a wing added on it and that wing never really fit with the rest of the building and they tended to hate each other and they'd come apart and go back together depending on the earth and how much moisture there was in the ground.
And they had it cabled together to keep it from falling apart.
And more than once I'd come back from somewhere and I'd find all my secretaries out on the other side of the street
arms akimbo and looking at it.
I said, what's the matter?
Was it a bomb threat?
And they said, no, no, all the telephone wires in the building snapped.
It moved apart like this and the wires that were taught would actually break.
So they'd have to come in and re-cable the building.
But we loved it.
It had half a level below ground level.
It had windows, but they were short windows and the
floor was like four or five feet below ground level, and I put all the grad students down there, and they called it the sump.
It was the sump where they said, there was a sign that said, where all the dirt and filth doth collect.
But that was their area, you know, and if the faculty wanted to see them on their own terms, they had to go to the sump.
So we had our own classrooms, we had our own offices, and that was really attractive.
And then, no, I misspoke myself.
That had oceanography and something else in that building.
When I was able to move them to this building after Goodwin, this is where the different business took place.
Here in Francis Hall.
In Francis.
And this was actually, that's where I had my first serious wrist slap because I had gotten on, I'd always been on good terms with the physical plant.
I knew how important that was to get on their scheduling list years ahead.
And so from Goodwin, I wanted this building when the business people vacated and also negotiated for the second floor of
next door where archaeology is.
Then, in the early 90s, I guess, other programs were building.
There was some talk about

A&M could no longer maintain all the different, we had to cut back on the number of degrees and the number of departments and the number of disciplines and focus on those that clearly had the potential of being national.
We thought we were, by then, well proven as national programs, but still didn't rate like the more traditional disciplines.
So I lost the
second floor where we had planned to have all of our extension built, but I was able to maintain this entire building even though there was a movement to take part of this way too.
That was my last gift to the department.
About when did you move into this building, into Francis?
I can't even tell you.
Ten years ago?
Yeah, around 90 or 91, something like that.
As the progress was going on in the 70s and then in the 80s, are there such things as national rankings of programs?
Yes.
Yeah, well, that's what helped because I was able to bring

bring back and still have somewhere in my local archives the and actually obviously I was very quick to send those on to the president's office where we were listed as number one or number two how soon in various how soon was that oh in the late 80s I think
10 years, 15 years into the life of the department.
How much?
We never, never would have gotten there without that ice cream cone concept because having that large number of full professors gave us the ability to turn out a large number of
of PhDs, and pretty soon you had an Aggie PhD in many of the leading departments around the country.
And they started to send their best students back here, so that network was invaluable.
All right, if there was a ranking today, where do you think the department's programs would rank?
I would hope in the top ten.
The problem is, if there is a problem, is that the field has evolved.
The world has changed.
When we built on the momentum of the Ork Commission
after World War II saying our parks are worn out, are inadequate, the people need new parks, massive amounts of money.
The Land and Water Conservation Fund was initiated with huge amounts of federal money going into new park development.
The Wilderness Act was passed, the Endangered Species Act.
We rode the crest of that tide all the way.
Then in the 90s, I guess you'd say,
that kind of dried up.
The environmental movement changed to an ecology preservation rather than a resource development.
Our strength was development of resources for recreation and park purposes.
I gave up the headship voluntarily over Kunkel's objections in
I said, 20 years is long enough.
He said, I don't want to accept that resignation.
I said, why?
He said, that's our tradition.
We don't do it that way at this school.
I said, how do you do it?
He said, well, you either become incompetent and get fired or you die.
And I said, I'm not willing to accept either of those.
I've had it.
I was really getting burned out, and I didn't realize I had a heart condition that was making me feel so tired.

but so i gave it up in 85 and i just felt like i wasn't able to maybe it was my own internal energy haskell but i didn't feel like i was really able to i've been a builder not a maintainer and i felt like it was becoming a maintaining job not a creating job i didn't maybe i didn't have a vision anymore but anyway it was hard to get things it was hard to get money it was hard to get outside grants

the department in the last since I retired in 94 so the last five or six years has gone a different direction the profs that taught resource management and facility design and administration and national parks are gone the younger faculty that have been hired
are interested more in the sociology of outdoor recreation.

In other words, the research being done is how do you feel about outdoor recreation and what value to you psychologically is it and doing surveys of visitors to see what can be provided to make their experience a happier experience, those kinds of things.

not to denigrate them not to say it isn't important but that's where the money is today and this and other departments have become more dependent they're chasing outside dollars to supplement the funds that come from the state and from tuition and so

the department currently is successful in a different direction than I let it and I don't mind that you know I did my thing my chapters over and done and closed it's a new chapter it's a different world if I were doing it now I might be doing the same thing because the big topics are at-risk youth making areas and facilities available for handicapped people
disadvantaged families, aberrant behavior, those kinds of topics.
It's not resource management.
Texas Tech still has a program.
No, they did away with it.
Oh, really?
Yeah, several years ago.
Are we the only one in the Southwest?
No, there are other smaller programs at San Marcos, I think maybe Huntsville.
When Ilo Urbanowski died, he stayed, well, when he retired, he stayed out for a few years as the living legend kind of thing, and was very unhappy for him, and that's why I've refused to do that.
But he decided to do that, but they eventually merged it with landscape architecture and then phased out the park over time.
So there really isn't a strong program at Tech anymore.
Who nationally,
would be the other, leave out A&M, who else would be near the top of the heap nationally these days?
Michigan State.
Again, much more community oriented than it was.
Penn State.
North Carolina State and Clemson.
University of Florida.
So they're all land grant that you've named so far.
Yeah.
Idaho has maintained the resource orientation, but that's where they are.
One of our graduates has been head at Chico, Cal State at Chico.
California has a number of good schools.
Cal State at Los Angeles and San Jose State and San Diego State, they're all the teachers colleges of the University of California system and they're highly urban in their focus.
So I think our department here at A&M now is much more like those other urban schools than it was
We were quite different, and there wasn't nearly the competition.
But I think our department here is doing very well in competing or co-leading in this arena of social service recreation or at-risk youth recreation, those kinds of things.
A while ago, you were giving well-deserved praise to President Rutter.
Looking back over your years here, which other presidents and vice presidents would you want to thank for their direct support and interest in the program?
Well, certainly,
The first that comes to my mind is Dean Kunkel, Harry Kunkel, because he probably supported things I was trying to do when I didn't deserve his support.
And I'm forever grateful for that.
I had some tough arguments with him, but that's as it should be.
If you can't prove, justify what you're doing, you don't deserve that.
In the early days, Potts
Dr. Potts was a strong supporter here.
When I got here, because it was a strange campus, Haskell, I really tried to become acquainted by personal visit.
When I had somebody new to meet, I tried to go to their office, meet them on their own turf, and then I had a mental picture of where they were and what they were doing rather than telephoning.
got an administrator here now that likes to work by computer even with internal memos.
Different styles for different people I guess.
Different world.
I've had so many warm colleagues on the campus.

Lineweaver was a tremendous help in those early days because he carried all, he banked all our students until we had our, I think the second or third year when we got our independent approvals for grad students with recreation and park, recreation and resource development titles.
then we could start to publicly claim our own.
Had pretty cordial relationships always with the coaching staff, the athletic department, naturally, because there was some affinity there, and especially with Randy Mattson.
oftentimes he was able to throw us some money to support different kinds of things that benefited the students.
You're saying Randy and his former student, he's one of my favorite.
Yeah.
Let's see, let's go to Kunkel a second.
What was Harry Kunkel's administrative operations methodology?
When you had a proposal request placed before him, how did he go about evaluating it, judging it?
Generally say no.
And then after a very fast no, okay.
you know, if you're really serious about this and we're gonna persist, okay, explain to me why we need to do this.
Did it take very long for him to reach a final conclusion?
No, no.
I think he, we dare not put this in, but I'm gonna leave it on while we talk, but I've got somewhere a secretarial
spiral thing that while I was here the three days interviewing I was writing down about different people, what I thought about President Rudder, what I thought about this one and that one that I met.
And a couple of years ago I pulled that out from wherever it is and said H.O.
Kunkel, German, hard headed, very pompous,
And, you know, that's how he came across at first to me.
But he, behind all that exterior, is a really wonderful guy, an intelligent person, good writer, a broad thinker.
I see.
That's a good summary.
Because to me, that's an accurate summary of Harry Kunkel.
That at first, he seems like a hard granite wall.
Mm.

but uh if you continue okay he would listen and so forth how important were the ag experiment station and extension services how important were they for your program well probably um the experiment station was critical couldn't well couldn't have couldn't have every one of the people i hired had
on the teaching faculty had a joint appointment with the Experiment Station.
If I'd been in any of the other nine colleges on the campus, I would have only had teaching money to work with, and consequently couldn't have hired as many people.
But either a lot of these were half and half in the early days,
So that really supplemented the money.
And it also made it attractive for faculty to come from other places.
Because instead of telling them you've got to teach four courses each semester, they had a reduced teaching loan.
Because they had 50% of their time and their effort was obligated to the experiment station.

And so there weren't very many places in the country that could offer that kind of, you know, you talk about 50 land grant institutions, but only six maybe, half a dozen of them that had programs like ours.
So we could really negotiate for the best people from around the country on that basis.
So Experiment Station was critical.
The extension, John Hutchinson wanted us to have an extension component, and he paid for similarly part appointments for a number of people.
But that was always smaller.
Didn't involve, I think when we were in the horse barn in 70, we had Jack Jones and Jack Sloan.
We had two full-time extension specialists,
in the state.
We never had enough Extension people to service the kind of demands we were getting on their time.
But Extension has always had a tough time like that dealing with districts and having enough specialists to handle the time.
John
Hutchinson, I would not call him niggardly, but he always had tremendous demands.
You know, I need six more pecan specialists, I need more soybean specialists, I need more this and that.
How do you rank your recreation people with that?
Plus our urban, our extension specialists were largely sought in the urban area.
And Hutchinson was very leery about getting involved in the urban areas at all because the extension
except for home economics, has largely been seen as a rural income enhancer.
Okay.
As a crystal ball gazer, with your background and what has been the Agricultural Extension Service, what could be done in urban areas by land grant schools to take
what used to be the ag extension service to the rural area, what could be done in the urban area of a similar public service nature?

Well it isn't too hard to you don't have to be a rocket scientist to figure that out look at look at the 4-H which is dramatically if you look at the 4-H membership in this state or any state I suspect 80 percent of their members are going to be urban kids and yet Extension has been successful in keeping the 4-H thing with you know which was a pet cow or a pig or a lamb or something
So that's the kind of thing that Extension could do.
Extension could... Oh, I haven't even thought of this.
This isn't my area.
I'm a park and tree people.
But the thing is that there should be just as big a role if Extension wanted to capitalize on it in working with these urban youth that are...
disadvantaged or hungry for opportunities.

Because couldn't we build a very good case for the recreational needs in an urban area where a person with extension, in quotation marks, where an extension person would go into that central city playground area
that recreational area and help those youngsters, help the parents.
Absolutely, and that's what Peter Witt and John Crompton are doing so successfully with this at-risk youth program, to catch them before they become delinquent and to show people why gangs are
are nothing but a manifestation of kids' desire to belong to something and be identified with something.
All right, so this department is 35 years old in round numbers today, this program.
Oh, Lord.
I guess.
You said that you were elected the president of the national group.
What are some other national or international marks of achievement by this program in that 35 years?
Oh, one thing I've been negligent in not highlighting is the tourism aspect.
It's become very, very well recognized in international tourism.
I belonged early to the International Federation for Park and Recreation Administration.
Claire Gunn has been a dominant figure in international work.
So has John Crompton.
And because of those
contacts and connection.
We have strong international ties, and we practically own the university system in Korea.
Because my son-in-law was over there diplomatically attached to the Eighth Air Force, and we went over and visited him twice,
I got one or two Koreans to come.
They made a pipeline.
Now there's more and more Koreans, and they've gone back.
And the major universities in Korea now are staffed with Texas A&M PhDs.
What about, are there national awards in this general area?
Yes.
David Witt just received.
